        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a bright-eyed, energetic 7-year-old girl from Brno, Czech Republic, who attends first grade at a local primary school. She loves drawing, playing with her younger brother in the backyard, and dancing at her weekly folk dance class. She lives at home with both parents and her brother; her mother works as a nurse and her father is an engineer.\n\n{patientName} was brought to the paediatric outpatient clinic by her mother on a Tuesday morning. She appears slightly tired and flushed, sitting quietly on the examination table clutching a stuffed rabbit. Her cheeks are rosy and she is breathing through her mouth. She complains of a sore, scratchy throat that started the previous evening, and her mother notes she woke during the night crying in discomfort [SNOMED:J02.9].\n\nOn examination the posterior pharyngeal wall is erythematous and mildly oedematous. {patientName} also reports a mild stomach ache [SNOMED:J02.9], which is common in children with acute pharyngitis. Temperature measured at triage is 38.4 °C. She has refused her breakfast and is drinking only small sips of warm tea. She has no rash and no difficulty breathing.\n\n{patientName} is generally a healthy child who attends school regularly and plays outdoors. Her vaccinations are up to date per the Czech national immunisation schedule. Her mother reports that several classmates have had similar symptoms over the past week, suggesting a possible epidemic spread within the school environment."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
